===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|legal}} [[expectancy|Expectancy]]; condition of ownership of real property being [[undetermined]]; lapse in succession of ownership of estate, or title. {{defdate|Late 16<sup>th</sup> century}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#: {{ux|en|The proceeds of the estate shall be held in '''abeyance''' in an escrow account until the minor reaches age twenty-one.}}
#* {{quote-book|passage=Yet sometimes the fee may be in '''''abeyance''''', that is (as the word signifies) in expectation, remembrance, and contemplation in law; there being no person in ''esse'', in whom it can vest and abide {{...}}|author=William Blackstone|title=Commentaries on the Laws of England|year=1765}}
# [[suspension|Suspension]]; temporary [[suppression]]; dormant condition. {{defdate|Mid 17<sup>th</sup> century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=2003|author={{w|Bill Bryson}}|title=A Short History of Nearly Everything|publisher=BCA|year_published=2003|page=376|passage=Without a plausible explanation for what might have provoked an ice age, the whole theory fell into '''abeyance'''.}}
# {{lb|en|heraldry}} [[expectancy|Expectancy]] of a title, its right in existence but its exercise suspended.
#: {{ux|en|The broad pennant of a commodore first class has been in '''abeyance''' since 1958, together with the rank.}}

